  <div class="cs-sec-head">[01] · context</div>
  <p class="cs-p">Enterprise analytics at Later meant serving five high-value clients — each $1M+ ARR — with dashboards across affiliate, paid, and organic channels. The early approach was pragmatic: write bespoke SQL per client, ship fast, move on. Three clients in, it was working. It was also quietly breaking. Every new client multiplied the maintenance surface: custom query logic per source, no shared models, upstream schema changes silently breaking one client's report without touching another's. Service desk tickets for ad hoc SQL fixes were the leading indicator that the architecture was wrong.</p>

  <div class="cs-sec-head">[02] · the decision</div>
  <p class="cs-p">The case to leadership was straightforward but uncomfortable: stop shipping the next client until we build the platform that ships all future clients faster. A four-week investment to normalize cross-source data into a unified dbt modelling layer — affiliate, paid, organic — in exchange for zero net-new SQL written per client from that point forward. Leadership pushed back. The preference was to keep shipping. The counter was explicit: every new client on bespoke SQL adds maintenance surface that compounds. A four-week investment now versus accumulating weeks of fragile maintenance per future client is not a close call.</p>

  <div class="cs-sec-head">[03] · outcome</div>
  <p class="cs-p">The unified dbt layer shipped. All five enterprise clients onboarded on shared infrastructure. Service desk ticket volume for ad hoc SQL fixes dropped 60%+ against the pre-migration baseline. New clients onboard on the same models — no net-new SQL written per client from client four onward. The schema normalization across affiliate, paid, and organic sources was the hard technical problem. Convincing leadership to pause delivery to make it happen was harder.</p>
